1","1478":"1466","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1438":"1438","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1438–1466":"1438–1466","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1459–1501":"1459–1501","1459":"1459","1437":"1437","1501":"1501","1478":"1466","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1438":"1438","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rebecca","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from the Latin form of the Hebrew name <i>Rebekah</i>, borne by the wife of Isaac, who was the mother of Esau and Jacob (Genesis 24–27). The Hebrew root occurs in the Bible only in the vocabulary word <i>marbek</i> ‘cattle stall’, and its connection with the name is doubtful. In any case, Rebecca was Aramean, and the name probably has a source in Aramaic. It has always been common as a Jewish name; in England and elsewhere it began to be used also by Christians from the 14th century onwards and especially at the time of the Reformation, when Old Testament names became popular. It was very common among the Puritans in the 17th century, and has enjoyed a tremendous vogue in England since the latter part of the 20th century, among people of many different creeds. In Scotland this is found as an Anglicized form of Beathag ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Pratt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname for a clever trickster, from Middle English <i>prat(te)</i>, <i>pret</i> ‘cunning, wily, astute’ (a derivative of Old English <i>præt</i>, <i>pret</i> ‘trickery, deception’, which is found in use as a byname in the 11th century). This surname is quite common in southeastern Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Pritt","meanings":["contracted form of <i>Birgit</i> (  see  Bridget  ), made famous in the English-speaking world by the Swedish actress  Britt Ekland  (  b. 1942 ; her surname was originally  Eklund )."]},{"name":"Pretty","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>pratti</i>, <i>prettie</i>, <i>pritti</i> ‘crafty, cunning’ (Old English <i>prættig</i>, <i>prettig</i>). Compare   Pratt  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":17,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Rebecca Pratt was born in 1438, in Somerset, England. She married Hugh Pruitt in 1459, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1466, in Norfolk, England, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1438–1466":"1438–1466","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1459–1501":"1459–1501","1459":"1459","1437":"1437","1501":"1501","1478":"1466","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1438":"1438","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1438–1466":"1438–1466","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1459–1501":"1459–1501","1459":"1459","1437":"1437","1501":"1501","1478":"1466","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1438":"1438","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1438–1466":"1438–1466","1437–1466":"1437–1466","1459–1501":"1459–1501","1459":"1459","1437":"1437","1501":"1501","1478":"1466","1466":"1466","1455":"1455","1438":"1438","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Angle